27:36.099 --> 27:55.823
contempt citation was voted, laying a 
legislative framework for having brought the

27:36.099 --> 27:55.823
question to me. It is not a witch hunt, because I'm 
down there trying to keep HUAC from putting the red

27:57.220 --> 28:06.112
label on Martin King. It is entirely that we are 
investigating oversight regarding the recent

28:07.093 --> 28:26.198
court decisions affecting the Internal Security 
Act of 1950, Title I, Title II, the Voorhees Act,

28:07.093 --> 28:26.198
the Smith Act, etc. They were all checking those 
laws out, and therefore they had to ask questions

28:28.883 --> 28:35.951
in order to advise Congress on how to improve the 
laws. Every bit of it was done with a statutory

28:36.932 --> 28:40.856
basis. But you get the FBI files on me. There were 12 
separate prosecutive summaries sent by Hoover to

28:42.998 --> 28:55.451
the Justice Department to prosecute me. Never 
just I mean, I would say that he hated my

28:57.329 --> 29:06.362
integration work, and he didn't like my work to 
abolish the Inter-American Identities

28:57.329 --> 29:06.362
Committee. And so it's a personal vendetta on an 
individual. And

29:08.865 --> 29:19.020
when you get these prosecuting summaries, which I 
have, there are six of them in that pile of papers

29:08.865 --> 29:19.020
you have right there. Under the FOIA, you get these 
documents. In every case, it's not just a wild...

29:26.641 --> 29:53.712
accusation against me they claimed that under the 
fbi's responsibility to enforce the federal

29:26.641 --> 29:53.712
criminal statutes namely smith act the police act 
security act county's control act we have

29:26.641 --> 29:53.712
investigated mr wilkins and we find that he is 
guilty of so-and-so they provide what all the

29:26.641 --> 29:53.712
agents that were following me at that time turn in 
all their stuff Hoover puts it into one three-page

29:54.367 --> 30:01.215
summary and turns it over for prosecution for my 
violating one of the acts. It's very important to

30:01.235 --> 30:04.459
know it's done that way. And then each of these was 
rejected. Twelve separate attorneys general,

30:08.744 --> 30:23.040
both Republican and Democrat, write back to 
Hoover saying the evidence you have submitted

30:08.744 --> 30:23.040
shows no indication of violation of federal 
criminal statutes on the part of Mr. Wilkinson. I

30:25.096 --> 30:37.734
throw this out to you because now we're building up 
a similar legislative history regarding the use

30:25.096 --> 30:37.734
of the word terrorism, and that's really the 
argument that I was making in Harvard. Because

30:38.716 --> 30:51.795
these witch hunts, these inquisitorial 
committees, these repressive laws

30:54.492 --> 31:05.423
are all done by men and women who maintain the 
pretense that we're a system, a government of

30:54.492 --> 31:05.423
laws. Yeah. It isn't just like, go get them, go 
smear them, go get Martin Luther King's sex life,

31:07.585 --> 31:14.152
go cop them. They always give you a legislative 
basis for doing what they're doing. And now that

31:19.758 --> 31:22.761
those laws have been declared either 
unconstitutional or unenforceable, which all of

31:23.281 --> 31:28.646
them have been. When they get around to 1981,

31:30.367 --> 31:51.246
five years after HUAC is abolished and Strom 
Thurmond revives HUAC in the Senate Judiciary

31:30.367 --> 31:51.246
Subcommittee, they find that there is no 
statutory basis that's solid enough in the word

31:30.367 --> 31:51.246
communism or certainly the word un-American, 
which doesn't even fly anymore. So it's called the

31:55.900 --> 31:59.405
Senate Judiciary Subcommittee on Terrorism. And 
when Hoover

32:00.406 --> 32:20.592
dies in 72, and Gerald Ford knocks out the

32:00.406 --> 32:20.592
FBI's quintile probe on political surveillance, 
and begins to turn the FBI around to a federal

32:00.406 --> 32:20.592
bureau of criminal investigation. It was his 
attorney general, Levy,

32:22.723 --> 32:32.792
under Ford, that gives us the protections. But in 
1983,

32:32.812 --> 32:49.428
William Fred Smith, attorney general under 
Reagan, now Meese, writes new guidelines that

32:32.812 --> 32:49.428
overturns Gerald Ford's guidelines. I think it's 
important. that it's a Republican today who's

32:50.592 --> 32:55.977
turning the clock back on a good Republican we had 
in 1976. And Reagan's new guidelines state that

32:57.759 --> 33:06.969
the FBI shall investigate all violations of 
federal criminal law, which is where they should

32:57.759 --> 33:06.969
stop. Nothing more, except maybe to repeal what we 
call the speech crimes. But get rid of the speech

33:16.518 --> 33:18.721
crimes and enforce the law. That's what the FBI 
should do. But then he doesn't. That is point A. B,

33:23.683 --> 33:28.049
the FBI shall investigate all terrorist 
enterprises. And that is the basis of what Mies is

33:29.731 --> 33:38.383
doing in infiltrating the church movement, the 
sanctuary, the Central America Peace Movement,

33:29.731 --> 33:38.383
and so on. The only thing I want to add for this 
record, and I did it not in Texas, where it might be

33:39.565 --> 33:51.160
popular, but I did it in Massachusetts in... Ted 
Kennedy's home district, a block away from the

33:51.545 --> 33:55.649
Kennedy School of Government. The guidelines 
that Ronald Reagan and William Brent Smith

33:57.130 --> 34:19.611
formalized in March of 1983 were copied after an 
original draft, which was never approved, done by

33:57.130 --> 34:19.611
Jimmy Carter in 1979 under his attorney general, 
Ben Civilletti, And the Carter Charter was

34:20.435 --> 34:28.586
written by and introduced by Senator Ted Kennedy. 
It was the liberals, Kennedy, Carter,

34:30.028 --> 34:42.425
Civilletti, that first came up with this loose 
word, terrorist enterprise, which goes to the

34:30.028 --> 34:42.425
heart of political dissent. It is undefined. I 
mean, we have all the laws we need for the FBI to stop

34:43.847 --> 34:49.935
terrorism. dynamiting, possession, 
kidnapping, hijacking. Those were all the books.

34:56.231 --> 34:57.833
Let the FBI enforce the law. That's what is needed. 
The church committee, late Senator Frank Church,

35:02.520 --> 35:12.455
committee report, which is so valuable, sort of 
the bible of the abuse of power by J. Edgar Hoover.

35:14.197 --> 35:19.585
They brought out the fact that in Chicago, from 
1966 to

35:22.822 --> 35:36.920
The FBI had 1,012 informants,

35:22.822 --> 35:36.920
political informants, on political 
surveillance in Chicago. They spent $2,500,000

35:36.940 --> 35:41.186
paying those informants. During that period of 
time, there were over 1,000 gangland murders in

35:42.007 --> 35:50.398
Chicago that were never caught by the FBI. in New 
York at the same time. There was one period in New

35:54.861 --> 36:06.497
York where the FBI had 404

35:54.861 --> 36:06.497
agents on the communist detail, and only four on 
organized crime. This is fact. This is out of

36:10.222 --> 36:11.644
congressional? Church Valley Report. Okay. Very 
basic. Incredible. The American Bar Association

36:21.665 --> 36:36.781
which, you know, is the respectable bar unit, you 
know, the officers of the court in our old system,

36:21.665 --> 36:36.781
did a critique of William French Smith's 
guidelines in 1983. And they asked correctly, why

36:38.023 --> 36:46.372
the need for this special focus on terrorism? Why 
does there need to be a special but why not just the

36:49.643 --> 36:51.965
federal criminal statutes? And they invite Judge 
Webster, the current director of the FBI, to come

36:52.606 --> 37:02.877
before the ABA and to tell them, what is the need for 
this? Do you need extra money to fight terrorism?

37:08.663 --> 37:17.393
And what is the empirical data to support such a 
concentration drive on domestic terrorism? And

37:18.474 --> 37:19.515
Judge Webster tells the ABA, this is a better 
public record, I do not need any more money to fight

37:19.698 --> 37:27.706
terrorism. Terrorism is a low priority. In 1981 
there were, these are very close to exact, in 1981

37:31.149 --> 37:42.720
there were 51 terrorist cases in the United 
States. In 1982 there were 40. In 1983, 31. In 1984,

37:46.444 --> 37:49.587
5. Well, there's no basis for it. It's a guise for 
silencing dissent. The international terrorist

37:56.154 --> 38:15.085
problem is being exploited by Reagan and by 
expedients, by Carter and Kennedy, as a means of

37:56.154 --> 38:15.085
rationalizing some control on dissent in this 
country. And, you know, I give this to you

38:16.803 --> 38:23.869
hurriedly in my capsule, but I've prepared very 
carefully for my lecture here. I'm dealing with

38:23.929 --> 38:30.535
300 of the brightest young law students in the 
country last Saturday. And I look at them, they're

38:31.816 --> 38:36.180
all, you know, under 25. They don't know these 
things. I know it. So I went back and pulled out the

38:39.863 --> 38:45.848
statutory, the legislative history to show how 
their generation is going to be impacted by these

38:46.587 --> 39:02.048
Reagan guidelines unless they get involved in 
civil liberties work and fight for the right to

38:46.587 --> 39:02.048
dissent. I have another question, and that is, 
that deals with the relationship between you and

39:02.809 --> 39:14.164
your organization, National Committee to 
Abolish HUAC, And the other one that you repeat, I

39:15.528 --> 39:21.154
don't get the question. I have another question. 
And that is the relationship between the National

39:23.577 --> 39:42.438
Committee to Abolish HUAC and then Carl and the 
movement, the anti-war movement, the women's

39:23.577 --> 39:42.438
liberation movement, the civil rights movement, 
what's basically called the movement in the

39:23.577 --> 39:42.438
1960s. What kinds of roles I know that you were 
working still very diligently to abolish HUAC

39:44.840 --> 39:51.888
during that time, but what else did you, and did you 
join in? What kind of relations did you have with

39:51.928 --> 39:55.893
the anti-war movement, the student movement, 
etc.? It's a very, very thoughtful question,

39:56.394 --> 40:13.834
because much of those movements in the 60s had an 
element that was anti-

40:15.113 --> 40:18.317
the word, not legislative politics, but 
electoral politics. Anti-electoral politics.

40:21.981 --> 40:28.649
My own kids, for example, dropped out of Cal and San 
Francisco State to become trade unions. The

40:28.669 --> 40:32.794
academic world was not real. And many, many people 
were turned off by electoral politics. The idea of

40:39.763 --> 40:43.247
lobbying to influence a member of Congress to stop 
the Vietnam War, or in our case, to abolish UAC,

40:45.033 --> 40:52.961
it's like we're hopelessly naÃ¯ve people who don't 
know what's going on. Yeah. We held our, N. Carl's

40:56.024 --> 41:01.410
strength has been focused. Our strength is the 
fact that we're absolutist on principle. We do not

41:06.655 --> 41:12.441
deviate

41:06.655 --> 41:12.441
a bit in regard to the political content of the Bill 
of Rights. We do not, as many people say, well, you

41:16.620 --> 41:27.469
know, all speech is all right except maybe a little 
bit, we ought to do something about the Nazis or the

41:16.620 --> 41:27.469
plan. We don't ever get near that. On wiretapping, 
where Ted Kennedy came up with a wiretapping bill a

41:29.791 --> 41:38.159
couple years ago, we fought it. All right, that's 
one thing. The second thing is, that we focus. We

41:45.461 --> 41:53.209
take the most imminent and dangerous issue for 
civil liberties at any one time, and then we focus.

41:54.371 --> 41:56.453
We don't try to cover the whole field. Now, during 
the 60s, we always have argued that civil

41:58.075 --> 42:12.330
liberties are indivisible to peace. Civil 
liberties are indivisible to civil rights, or

42:12.968 --> 42:17.434
whatever the movements are. During the civil 
rights struggles, Ann Braden, N. Carl officer,

42:17.474 --> 42:31.451
wrote our booklet called HUAC, Bulwark of 
Segregation, in which we brought together the

42:17.474 --> 42:31.451
civil rights movement and civil liberties. Today 
on our board of officers, we have John Lewis, the

42:32.252 --> 42:42.705
first president of SNCC, Julian Bond, the PR guy in 
SNCC, now a senator in Georgia, C.T. Vivian, who

42:43.861 --> 42:47.106
was director of affiliates for Martin Luther 
King. They're all our officers because we related

42:47.126 --> 42:53.976
the civil rights struggles with civil liberties. 
And Martin King's statement the night we went to

42:53.996 --> 42:58.663
jail is the classic. On the peace movement, always 
the same, but we had to do an awful lot of education.

43:05.834 --> 43:12.203
In 1962, right after I got out of prison, I came back 
to Los Angeles. And you

43:13.499 --> 43:29.323
held a hearing against students at three of our 
colleges, some student peace activity or I don't

43:13.499 --> 43:29.323
know what it was. Yeah. We had done such an 
organizing job among students that when the

43:30.304 --> 43:42.122
hearing was held, we had the long-standing 
federal building surrounded on four sides that

43:30.304 --> 43:42.122
makes 20 story building, four of us were students 
going around there. Beautiful demonstration,

43:47.141 --> 43:50.884
something you never saw during the silent 
fifties. It came by 62. It began in 1960

43:52.887 --> 44:00.454
when we had the first demonstration. I'm actually 
accused of organizing the so-called riot at San

44:00.554 --> 44:10.725
Francisco City Hall where the students were 
washed down the stairs of the city hall. That's

44:10.975 --> 44:17.525
when it began, after Carol Chessman, and after the 
Greensboro Civil Rights guy. I trace all of the

44:17.545 --> 44:26.359
development of the student movements to the 
Greensboro black students who fought for the

44:17.545 --> 44:26.359
World Restoration. I think that's where it began. 
But by 1962, they're there. Now, that morning,

44:30.465 --> 44:38.738
I've been working for years with a group starting 
about 1960. called Women Strike for Peace, headed

44:39.359 --> 44:43.303
up by Dagmar Wilson. They were fighting Kennedy at 
that point for his bomb test in the Pacific, and

44:43.664 --> 44:53.975
getting nowhere with it. And so they had decided, 
as a tactic, that if anyone should read in the

44:53.995 --> 45:08.792
papers that Kennedy had dropped another bomb in 
South Pacific, I mean a test of a bomb in the South

44:53.995 --> 45:08.792
Pacific, that without any further word, All 100 
members of WISP, Women's Strike for Peace, would

45:09.734 --> 45:14.620
come to the federal building. They'd wear white 
dresses, and they'd carry a red rose or a yellow

45:15.340 --> 45:25.052
rose, something like that, and do a vigil against 
Kennedy. The night before the U.S. hearings

45:25.072 --> 45:31.079
began, Kennedy dropped a bomb, passed a bomb. The 
next morning, promptly at 9 o'clock, from all over

45:31.099 --> 45:39.268
the city, without even a phone call, are 100 women 
in white dresses, with little red roses to

45:39.653 --> 45:42.495
protest. They get down there, and they can't get 
near the Federal Building because the students

45:43.036 --> 45:51.603
are four abreast all around it. They don't know the 
students. They do know me. So they call me, come

45:56.707 --> 46:05.155
across the street to them, and they said, Frank, 
Kennedy has tested another bomb. We're down here

46:05.915 --> 46:09.238
to do a vigil. Could you ask the students to make 
some room so we can do a vigil in front of the Federal

46:09.893 --> 46:21.226
Building there against Kennedy?" And I turned and 
said, look at that. How can you, how can you do that?

46:27.032 --> 46:32.959
There's no place you can, the building, the 
headline of the day said, HUAC used a freight

46:27.032 --> 46:32.959
elevator. You can get in the building. They had to 
use a freight elevator to get into the building. I

46:38.632 --> 46:40.655
said, come on over and join them. And they said, no, 
that would confuse the issues between HUAC and the

46:42.197 --> 46:51.850
Kennedy bomb testing. We cannot confuse the 
issues. That was April of 62. On December the 6th of

46:56.597 --> 47:07.812
62, I got a phone call from Dagmar Wilson in 
Washington saying, HUAC has just subpoenaed the

47:08.197 --> 47:12.503
entire leadership of Women's Strike for Peace, 
will you come back and help us?" And I went back to

47:13.545 --> 47:14.646
help. They didn't need any help. They did the most 
magnificent opposition I'd ever seen, where all

47:16.088 --> 47:21.996
these women go into a U.I. hearing, bring their 
babies with unchanged diapers, and put all the

47:22.037 --> 47:32.331
women in the front row, and when the first witness 
is called, by signal, every woman change his dirty

47:32.902 --> 47:35.714
diapers in front of UX. Stench was greater than UX. 
